<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,867,1974]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,286,868,894]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Etymology.</emphasis>
Despite O. 
<bibRefCitation author="Pickard-Cambridge, O." box="[424,726,867,894]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" pagination="423 - 442" refId="ref10145" refString="Pickard-Cambridge, O. (1882) On new genera and species of Araneidea. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 1882, 423 - 442. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1882. tb 02749. x" type="journal article" year="1882">Pickard-Cambridge (1882)</bibRefCitation>
having established the combination 
<taxonomicName authorityName="O. Pickard-Cambridge" authorityYear="1882" box="[1144,1296,868,893]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Mago" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intenta">
<emphasis box="[1144,1296,868,893]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Mago intenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the 
<typeStatus box="[1388,1436,868,894]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">type</typeStatus>
species, which suggests he deliberately considered the genus to be feminine in gender, the name 
<taxonomicName box="[1248,1313,904,929]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Mago" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1248,1313,904,929]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Mago</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears in classic literature being related only to men. In fact, “ 
<taxonomicName box="[730,800,940,966]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Mago" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mago</taxonomicName>
” was a common name used for men in Ancient Carthage, having been given to notorious Carthaginian people, such as a king and the man known as the “father of agriculture”, among others (Perseus Digital Library). 
<bibRefCitation author="Simon, E." box="[680,836,1011,1038]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" pagination="27 - 61" refId="ref10382" refString="Simon, E. (1900) Etudes arachnologiques. 30 e Memoire. XLVII. Descriptions d'especes nouvelles de la famille des Attidae. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, 69, 27 - 61." type="journal article" year="1900">Simon (1900)</bibRefCitation>
considered the genus to be masculine in gender, and described, for instance, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1900" box="[415,537,1048,1073]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Mago" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vicanus">
<emphasis box="[415,537,1048,1073]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">M. vicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1900" box="[589,689,1048,1073]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Mago" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pexus">
<emphasis box="[589,689,1048,1073]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">M. pexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(masculine epithets). Simon’s gender correction was later followed by more recent researchers, such as 
<bibRefCitation author="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de" box="[571,796,1083,1110]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" pagination="175 - 197" refId="ref9775" refString="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de (1940) Spiders of the Guiana forest collected by O. W. Richards. Arquivos de Zoologia do Estado de Sao Paulo, 2, 175 - 197." type="journal article" year="1940">Mello-Leitão (1940</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de" box="[810,869,1084,1110]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" pagination="147 - 245" refId="ref9813" refString="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de (1943) Catalogo das aranhas do Rio Grande do Sul. Arquivos do Museu Nacional do Rio de Janeiro, 37, 147 - 245." type="journal article" year="1943">1943</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de" box="[883,942,1083,1110]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" pagination="213 - 302" refId="ref9847" refString="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de (1945) Aranas de Misiones, Corrientes y Entre Rios. Revista del Museo de La Plata, New Series, Zoology, 4, 213 - 302." type="journal article" year="1945">1945</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de" box="[955,1015,1084,1110]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" pagination="1 - 34" refId="ref9884" refString="Mello-Leitao, C. F. de (1947) Aranhas de Carmo do Rio Claro (Minas Gerais) coligidas pelo naturalista Jose C. M. Carvalho. Boletim do Museu Nacional do Rio de Janeiro, New Series, Zoology, 80, 1 - 34." type="journal article" year="1947">1947</bibRefCitation>
), 
<bibRefCitation author="Caporiacco, L. di" box="[1037,1251,1083,1110]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" pagination="45 - 193" refId="ref9230" refString="Caporiacco, L. di (1954) Araignees de la Guyane Francaise du Museum d'Histoire Naturelle de Paris. Commentationes Pontificia Academia Scientiarum, 16, 45 - 193." type="journal article" year="1954">Caporiacco (1954)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Galiano, M. E." box="[1266,1431,1083,1109]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" pagination="273 - 470" refId="ref9322" refString="Galiano, M. E. (1963) Las especies americanas de aranas de la familia Salticidae descriptas por Eugene Simon: Redescripciones basadas en los ejemplares tipicos. Physis, Revista de la Sociedad Argentina de Ciencias Naturales, (C), 23, 273 - 470." type="journal article" year="1963">Galiano (1963</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Galiano, M. E." box="[151,210,1119,1146]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" pagination="267 - 360" refId="ref9373" refString="Galiano, M. E. (1968) Revision de los generos Acragas, Amycus, Encolpius, Hypaeus, Mago y Noegus (Salticidae, Araneae). Revista del Museo Argentino de Ciencias Naturales Bernardino Rivadavia, Entomologia, 2, 267 - 360." type="journal article" year="1968">1968</bibRefCitation>
), 
<bibRefCitation author="Patello, T. J. C. &amp; Ruiz, G. R. S." box="[231,479,1119,1146]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" pagination="443 - 457" refId="ref10193" refString="Patello, T. J. C. &amp; Ruiz, G. R. S. (2014) Revision of the acutidens group of Mago (Araneae: Salticidae: Amycinae). Zootaxa, 3786 (4), 443 - 457. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3786.4.3" type="journal article" year="2014">Patello &amp; Ruiz (2014)</bibRefCitation>
and Costa &amp; Ruiz (2017).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,867,1974]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1155,1182]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[327,392,1156,1181]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Mago" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[327,392,1156,1181]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Mago</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily identified as an amycine for having pluridentate chelicera and the 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1237,1251,1154,1168]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">rd</superScript>
leg much longer than the 4 
<superScript attach="left" box="[264,277,1190,1204]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">th</superScript>
(
<figureCitation box="[293,511,1191,1218]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–27" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1980,2005]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,1509,1950]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,1500,1960]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 18–27. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 18–22 male (18 palp; 19 leg I; 20 leg II; 21 leg III; 22 leg IV, lateral); 23–27 female (23 palp; 24 leg I; 25 leg II; 26 leg III; 27 leg IV, lateral). Scale bar equals carapace length." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373147/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Figs 21–22, 26–27</figureCitation>
), difference proportionally larger than in most amycines (compare to 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 39–48" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1399,1424]" captionTargetBox="[151,1427,943,1379]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1427,943,1379]" captionText="FIGURES 39–48. Matinta acutidens: 39–43 male (39 palp; 40 leg I; 41 leg II; 42 leg III; 43 leg IV, lateral); 44–48 female (44 palp; 45 leg I; 46 leg II; 47 leg III; 48 leg IV, lateral). Scale bar equals carapace length." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3445821" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3445821/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Figs 42–43, 47–48</figureCitation>
, for instance). Among amycines, 
<taxonomicName box="[596,661,1228,1253]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Mago" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[596,661,1228,1253]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Mago</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
gathers small, dark, ground dwelling species with compact carapaces (thoracic region short, causing an abrupt slope; see 
<figureCitation box="[717,787,1263,1290]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1387,1412]" captionTargetBox="[159,1429,552,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,546,1368]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Mago intentus, male: 1 dorsal; 2 carapace, lateral; 3 right chelicera, frontal; 4 mouthparts and sternum, ventral; 5 endites and labium, distal." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373139/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Figs 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[797,871,1263,1290]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1423,1448]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1404]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,561,1404]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 14–16 male (14 face; 15 left chelicera, ventral; 16 lateral); 17 female, lateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373145/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">16–17</figureCitation>
). The male palp has the patella longer than the tibia (
<figureCitation box="[159,261,1299,1326]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–9" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1373,1398]" captionTargetBox="[166,1420,499,1343]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,489,1353]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 6–9. Mago intentus, male left palp: 6 ventral; 7 retrolateral; 8 dorsal; 9 retrolateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373141/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Figs 8–9</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[273,302,1300,1326]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–34" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1723,1748]" captionTargetBox="[166,1423,469,1701]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,453,1704]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 28–34. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 28–32 male (28 left palp, ventral; 29 same, retrolateral; 30 mouthparts, ventral; 31 same, laterodistal; 32 sternum and left coxae, ventral); 33–34 epigyne (33 ventral; 34 cleared, dorsal)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373149/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">29</figureCitation>
) and the femur with several dorsal spines (
<figureCitation box="[791,864,1299,1326]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–9" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1373,1398]" captionTargetBox="[166,1420,499,1343]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,489,1353]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 6–9. Mago intentus, male left palp: 6 ventral; 7 retrolateral; 8 dorsal; 9 retrolateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373141/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Figs 9</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[877,908,1300,1326]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–34" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1723,1748]" captionTargetBox="[166,1423,469,1701]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,453,1704]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 28–34. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 28–32 male (28 left palp, ventral; 29 same, retrolateral; 30 mouthparts, ventral; 31 same, laterodistal; 32 sternum and left coxae, ventral); 33–34 epigyne (33 ventral; 34 cleared, dorsal)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373149/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">29</figureCitation>
), besides expanded male endite tips (
<figureCitation box="[1329,1431,1299,1326]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1387,1412]" captionTargetBox="[159,1429,552,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,546,1368]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Mago intentus, male: 1 dorsal; 2 carapace, lateral; 3 right chelicera, frontal; 4 mouthparts and sternum, ventral; 5 endites and labium, distal." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373139/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Figs 4–5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,226,1336,1362]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–34" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1723,1748]" captionTargetBox="[166,1423,469,1701]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,453,1704]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 28–34. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 28–32 male (28 left palp, ventral; 29 same, retrolateral; 30 mouthparts, ventral; 31 same, laterodistal; 32 sternum and left coxae, ventral); 33–34 epigyne (33 ventral; 34 cleared, dorsal)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373149/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">30–31</figureCitation>
). The epigyne resembles those of species within other amycine genera, such as 
<taxonomicName box="[1132,1216,1336,1361]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Noegus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1132,1216,1336,1361]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Noegus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1900" box="[1273,1371,1336,1361]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Hypaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1273,1371,1336,1361]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Hypaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with an atrium on the epigynal plate and elongate digitiform glandular ducts on the copulation duct (
<figureCitation box="[1229,1313,1371,1398]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–34" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1723,1748]" captionTargetBox="[166,1423,469,1701]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,453,1704]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 28–34. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 28–32 male (28 left palp, ventral; 29 same, retrolateral; 30 mouthparts, ventral; 31 same, laterodistal; 32 sternum and left coxae, ventral); 33–34 epigyne (33 ventral; 34 cleared, dorsal)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373149/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
), but those genera do not include dark, compact species with such peculiar carapace.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,867,1974]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,452,1443,1470]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Common characters.</emphasis>
Small jumping spiders (about 
<quantity box="[807,896,1443,1470]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" unit="mm" value="3.5">3.5 mm</quantity>
) with compact dark bodies (
<figureCitation box="[1224,1357,1443,1470]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–13" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1674,1699]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,381,1654]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1435,381,1654]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 10–13. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 10–12 male (10 dorsal; 11 laterodorsal; 12 frontal); 13 female, dorsal. © 2015 W. Maddison, released under a Creative Commons Attribution (CC-BY) 3.0 license." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373143/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Figs 10–13</figureCitation>
). Male clypeus with strong whitish/yellowish moustache (
<figureCitation box="[716,799,1479,1506]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–13" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1674,1699]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,381,1654]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1435,381,1654]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 10–13. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 10–12 male (10 dorsal; 11 laterodorsal; 12 frontal); 13 female, dorsal. © 2015 W. Maddison, released under a Creative Commons Attribution (CC-BY) 3.0 license." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373143/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Chelicera pluridentate, small and vertical in both sexes, with mastidion in males (
<figureCitation box="[434,535,1515,1542]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1387,1412]" captionTargetBox="[159,1429,552,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,546,1368]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Mago intentus, male: 1 dorsal; 2 carapace, lateral; 3 right chelicera, frontal; 4 mouthparts and sternum, ventral; 5 endites and labium, distal." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373139/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Figs 3–4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[547,621,1515,1542]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1423,1448]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1404]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,561,1404]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 14–16 male (14 face; 15 left chelicera, ventral; 16 lateral); 17 female, lateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373145/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">14–16</figureCitation>
). Male palp with slightly curved femur (
<figureCitation box="[1072,1145,1515,1542]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–9" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1373,1398]" captionTargetBox="[166,1420,499,1343]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,489,1353]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 6–9. Mago intentus, male left palp: 6 ventral; 7 retrolateral; 8 dorsal; 9 retrolateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373141/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Figs 9</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1157,1189,1516,1542]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–34" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1723,1748]" captionTargetBox="[166,1423,469,1701]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,453,1704]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 28–34. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 28–32 male (28 left palp, ventral; 29 same, retrolateral; 30 mouthparts, ventral; 31 same, laterodistal; 32 sternum and left coxae, ventral); 33–34 epigyne (33 ventral; 34 cleared, dorsal)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373149/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">29</figureCitation>
); a curved RTA pointing dorsally and rounded RvTA (
<figureCitation box="[531,635,1551,1577]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–9" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1373,1398]" captionTargetBox="[166,1420,499,1343]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,489,1353]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 6–9. Mago intentus, male left palp: 6 ventral; 7 retrolateral; 8 dorsal; 9 retrolateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373141/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Figs 6–9</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[649,724,1552,1578]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–34" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1723,1748]" captionTargetBox="[166,1423,469,1701]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,453,1704]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 28–34. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 28–32 male (28 left palp, ventral; 29 same, retrolateral; 30 mouthparts, ventral; 31 same, laterodistal; 32 sternum and left coxae, ventral); 33–34 epigyne (33 ventral; 34 cleared, dorsal)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373149/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">28–29</figureCitation>
); reduced tegulum with large “amycoid loop” in spermophore (
<bibRefCitation author="Ruiz, G. R. S. &amp; Maddison, W. P." box="[159,431,1587,1614]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" pagination="251 - 279" refId="ref10318" refString="Ruiz, G. R. S. &amp; Maddison, W. P. (2015) The new Andean jumping spider genus Urupuyu and its placement within a revised classification of the Amycoida (Araneae: Salticidae). Zootaxa, 4040 (3), 251 - 279. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4040.3.1" type="journal article" year="2015">Ruiz &amp; Maddison 2015</bibRefCitation>
); embolus generally curling around tegulum, varying in length, from short (arch of about 180°, 
<figureCitation box="[219,300,1623,1650]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–34" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1723,1748]" captionTargetBox="[166,1423,469,1701]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,453,1704]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 28–34. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 28–32 male (28 left palp, ventral; 29 same, retrolateral; 30 mouthparts, ventral; 31 same, laterodistal; 32 sternum and left coxae, ventral); 33–34 epigyne (33 ventral; 34 cleared, dorsal)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373149/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
) to long (&gt;540°, 
<figureCitation box="[495,563,1623,1650]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–9" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1373,1398]" captionTargetBox="[166,1420,499,1343]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,489,1353]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 6–9. Mago intentus, male left palp: 6 ventral; 7 retrolateral; 8 dorsal; 9 retrolateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373141/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
), with tip resting in cymbial groove. Generalized leg spination for both sexes (based on 
<taxonomicName authority="Ruiz &amp; Maddison &amp; Galiano, 2019" authorityName="Ruiz &amp; Maddison &amp; Galiano" authorityYear="2019" box="[269,412,1660,1686]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Mago" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brimodes" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[269,412,1660,1686]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">M. brimodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[421,512,1660,1686]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[421,512,1660,1686]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
): femur I d1-1-1, II d1-1-1, p1di, III d1-1-1, p0 (or p2di), IV d1-1-0; patella I, II 0, III, IV 0 (or r1); tibia I 
<date box="[446,498,1696,1722]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">v2-2</date>
-2 (median pair may be asymmetrical), II 
<date box="[972,998,1696,1722]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">v1</date>
r-2-2, p1 (or 0-1), III p1 (or 0-1), r1-1, 
<date box="[151,177,1731,1757]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">v1</date>
rdi, IV p0, r1-1, v0; metatarsus I, II 
<date box="[582,636,1732,1758]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">v2-2</date>
, III p1-2, r1-2, 
<date box="[809,835,1732,1758]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">v1</date>
r-1r (or 
<date box="[925,951,1732,1758]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">v1</date>
r-2), IV p0-1, r0-1 (or 1-1d), 
<date box="[1279,1305,1732,1758]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">v1</date>
p-1r. Abdomen small and rounded in both sexes. Epigyne with an anterior small atrium (
<figureCitation box="[1018,1101,1767,1794]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–34" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1723,1748]" captionTargetBox="[166,1423,469,1701]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,453,1704]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 28–34. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 28–32 male (28 left palp, ventral; 29 same, retrolateral; 30 mouthparts, ventral; 31 same, laterodistal; 32 sternum and left coxae, ventral); 33–34 epigyne (33 ventral; 34 cleared, dorsal)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373149/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
), with simple ducts leading to spermathecae, with digitiform glands in the middle portion of copulatory ducts (
<figureCitation box="[1049,1180,1803,1830]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–34" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1723,1748]" captionTargetBox="[166,1423,469,1701]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,453,1704]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 28–34. Mago brimodes sp. nov.: 28–32 male (28 left palp, ventral; 29 same, retrolateral; 30 mouthparts, ventral; 31 same, laterodistal; 32 sternum and left coxae, ventral); 33–34 epigyne (33 ventral; 34 cleared, dorsal)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3373149/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Figs 33–34</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,867,1974]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1839,1866]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known from 
<collectingCountry box="[511,604,1839,1865]" name="Ecuador" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
and, possibly, 
<collectingCountry box="[771,839,1839,1865]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(the specific locality in the Amazon for the 
<typeStatus box="[1334,1382,1840,1866]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">type</typeStatus>
species is unknown).
</paragraph>
